        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Three of the original woodcuts for the first edition, which John Murray had presumably obtained from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1004.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Henry Colburn</ref>, with one further woodcut of the scissor-beak bird (<hi rend="italic">Rhynchops nigra</hi>, a synonym of <hi rend="italic">Rynchops niger</hi>, the black skimmer) made at Murray’s expense (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-872.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to John Murray, [31 May 1845]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The remaining woodcuts were borrowed from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4407.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Smith, Elder &amp; Co</ref>., the publishers of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1571.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Coral reefs</hi></ref> and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8001.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Volcanic islands</hi></ref>. See letters to John Murray, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-872.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">[31 May 1845]</ref> and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-896.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">[27 July 1845]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3470.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hearne 1795</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">In the headnote to ‘The complaint of a forsaken Indian woman’, which appeared originally in <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5243.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Wordsworth’s</ref> <hi rend="italic">Lyrical ballads</hi> (1798).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2157.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Drury 1729</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
